Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0602023E, Project ACS-01.

Title: Albatross                                                                                                                      21.865             -            -
Description: The Albatross program is exploring new technologies to enable perpetually flying aircraft. Albatross approaches
this by creating a bird-like soaring capability for small-unmanned aircraft systems (s-UAS) that leverages weather forecast-
informed mission planning and real-time sensing of dynamic wind conditions to autonomously navigate s-UAS and extend flight
endurance and range. Current estimates indicate that Albatross soaring techniques could reduce average flight power by 75%
for relevant missions. Albatross is also developing autonomous guidance, navigation, and controls to harness soaring sources
while maintaining safe separation from terrain. Albatross will use a series of real-world flight events to mature and demonstrate
capability incrementally. Technologies developed under this program will be demonstrated on mature platforms to support rapid
transition to the Services.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0602023E, Project ACS-01.

Title: Lunar Assay via Small Satellite Orbiter (LASSO)                                                                                 2.156             -            -
Description: The Lunar Assay via Small Satellite Orbiter (LASSO) program will optimize autonomous navigation and propulsion
in support of advancing Space Situational Awareness capabilities in cislunar space. The program will build a low-cost satellite,
launched as a secondary payload, to demonstrate these capabilities in Very Low Lunar Orbit (VLLO), which is the most
challenging environment in cislunar space due to continually destabilizing orbits, lack of navigation aids (i.e., GPS), variable
gravity and operation in close proximity to terrain. While operating in VLLO, LASSO will collect high-resolution data regarding
accessible water ice on the moon by capturing data about resource distribution and quantities to support future in-situ resource
utilization (ISRU) investigation. Such discoveries support future lunar exploration. With improved navigation, propulsion, and
autonomous control, the LASSO satellite will achieve persistent VLLO while building a statistically significant understanding of
lunar resources.

Beginning in FY 2026, this program will be funded in PE 0602023E, Project ACS-01.

Title: Persistent Optical Wireless Energy Relay (POWER)                                                                                3.892             -            -
Description: The Persistent Optical Wireless Energy Relay (POWER) program designed, built, and validated foundational
components for effective optical energy relays. These relays will enable a ground-based laser to efficiently transmit energy over
100s of kilometers leveraging a high-altitude transmission layer which minimizes atmospheric absorption and scattering. The high-
altitude energy relay nodes will redirect, correct, and selectively harvest energy from the optical energy source and then beam

