INSERT INTO public.pe_narratives (pe_id, fiscal_year, mission_description, justification, accomplishments, planned_program, performance_metrics, other_program_funding, raw_text, content_hash, section_hashes, source_pdf, source_page, ingested_at) VALUES ($$0604850N$$, 2027, $$The National Defense Strategy (NDS) requires the United States to have the most lethal and capable military in the world. The U.S. Navy must meet the rising challenge
by delivering a new attack submarine to maintain superiority in the undersea domain. SSN(X) will significantly contribute to rebuilding our military, reinforcing deterrence
in the undersea, and building lethality in the Joint Force. It will provide enhanced lethality, survivability, speed and operational availability to maintain undersea
supremacy against growing threats. SSN(X) will conduct full spectrum undersea warfare and employ and coordinate with Robotic and Autonomous Systems (RAS) and
sensors as a force multiplier. It will retain and improve multi-mission (Anti-Surface Warfare (ASuW), Anti-Submarine Warfare (ASW), Subsea Seabed Warfare (SSW),
Strike, Special Operating Forces (SOF), Mine, and Intelligence, Surveillance and Reconnaissance (ISR)) capability and sustained combat presence in denied waters.
SSN(X) will operate independently or be integrated within a Task Force.

The formal acquisition strategy for SSN(X) will be drafted following Milestone A. The approved Material Development Decision (MDD) designated the SSN(X) a pre-
Major Defense Acquisition Program (MDAP), Acquisition Category (ACAT) IB in FY 2025. Preliminary Design for SSN(X) will be accomplished through a proven,
collaborative Navy-Industry effort to maximize the benefits of industry and the potential shipbuilders. The Future Attack Submarine Analysis of Alternatives (AoA)
concluded in November 2025 and determined a clean sheet design is required to respond to the high-end threat.

FY 2027 budget will help deliver increased warfighting performance through larger payload volume, improved lethality and survivability, and organic hosting RAS for
Lead Ship Authorization as early as 2040.

FY 2026 completed the AoA, which was extended due to additional analysis efforts; continued technology development efforts; and shipbuilder design studies. Targeted
technology development with Virginia Class Block VII and VIII will continue to reduce risk. SSN(X) will incorporate the best practices and lessons learned from the
VIRGINIA Class.
autonomous system integration, etc.), Capability Development Document (CDD) development, and Ship Specification development. Continued common technology
