 concepts, prototyping, modifications to existing test facilities, and preparing all required acquisition documentation.$$, $$SSN(X) will be designed to enter, fight, and deny within heavily defended adversary bastions from the sea to the seabed. SSN(X) will deliver increased warfighting
performance through larger payload volume, improved lethality and survivability, and organic hosting of Robotic and Autonomous Systems (RAS). These capabilities
assure access to threat-denied areas, deny adversary safe havens, and ensure flexibility. This project encompasses Navy RDT&E efforts required to design the next
SSN.

